        "timestamp": 1782264686
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span aria-label=\"memo\" class=\"emoji emoji-1f4dd\" role=\"img\" title=\"memo\">:memo:</span> fitzgen submitted <a href=\"https://github.com/bytecodealliance/wasmtime/pull/13711#pullrequestreview-4558413663\">PR review</a>.</p>",
        "id": 606131271,
        "sender_full_name": "Wasmtime GitHub notifications bot",
        "timestamp": 1782264895
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span aria-label=\"speech balloon\" class=\"emoji emoji-1f4ac\" role=\"img\" title=\"speech balloon\">:speech_balloon:</span> fitzgen created <a href=\"https://github.com/bytecodealliance/wasmtime/pull/13711#discussion_r3464016291\">PR review comment</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>I initially was trying to minimize changes by leaving the return block as-is, but switching it over as well means that basically all blocks are handled uniformly now (using variables instead of block params) except for two cases:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>The entry block, which has function params</li>\n<li>Exception blocks, which take the payload as params</li>\n</ol>\n<p>However, both of these kinds of blocks are never targeted for branching directly by e.g. <code>br_if</code> in Wasm so they can never have Wasm stack operand params, so our handling of Wasm branch targets can still be uniform. I think this leaves us in a pretty nice place, but I'm curious what your opinion is too.</p>\n<p>See also <a href=\"https://github.com/bytecodealliance/wasmtime/pull/13711/commits/c20864c1e2e33011e3d1c638232d2c8da64633b7\">https://github.com/bytecodealliance/wasmtime/pull/13711/commits/c20864c1e2e33011e3d1c638232d2c8da64633b7</a></p>\n</blockquote>",
        "id": 606131272,
        "sender_full_name": "Wasmtime GitHub notifications bot",
        "timestamp": 1782264895
    },
